<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  <a href="/intents/">Intents</a> are ratified as <strong>UX-only and open</strong>
  (<code>docs/agent/platform-decisions.md:378</code>, <em>intents-are-UX-only</em>):
  <em>"Intents are an open, never-finished system: custom non-standard intents must coexist conflict-free —
  standardize the meta-schema, not the list."</em> That promise is <strong>unrealized</strong>: WE ships a
  fixed catalog (<code>src/_data/intents/*.json</code>) with no seam for a product to mint and use its
  <em>own</em> intent. Decision
  <a href="/backlog/1913-realize-app-authored-custom-intents-meta-schema-registry-for/">#1913</a> asks for the
  shape: how a product <strong>declares</strong> a custom intent (the meta-schema), <strong>registers</strong>
  it conflict-free against the standard catalog (namespacing), and whether resolution against the trait
  resolver (<code>webtraits/intentProfileResolver.ts</code>) is <strong>build-time</strong> or
  <strong>runtime</strong>. The principle is settled; the registry/authoring shape is the open call.
</p>
<p>
  This is squarely a <a href="/research/">native-first</a> question — "prefer patterns that mirror how the web
  platform itself handles extensibility." So the survey leads with the platform's own answers
  (custom elements, CSS custom properties, custom states) and reads the tooling/schema precedents
  (Design Tokens, JSON Schema/OpenAPI, Tailwind, reverse-DNS/scope registries) as corroboration or caution.
</p>

<h2>Prior art at a glance</h2>
