<h2>Finding 1 — the native pattern for namespacing is a reserved structural marker, not a managed prefix table</h2>
<p>
  The three web-platform precedents converge on the <em>same</em> device. Custom elements require a
  <strong>mandatory hyphen</strong>; the WHATWG rationale is explicit — the dash is for "namespacing and
  forward compatibility (since no elements will be added to HTML, SVG, or MathML with hyphen-containing local
  names going forward)." CSS custom properties use the <strong><code>--</code></strong> marker, and MDN states
  the guarantee plainly: <em>"&lt;dashed-ident&gt;s will never be defined in CSS."</em> Custom states
  <em>originally</em> reused that very <code>--</code> marker (<code>:--checked</code>) for the identical
  reason. DTCG generalizes it to a sigil: the <strong>leading <code>$</code></strong> is reserved for
  format properties so <em>"token and group names MUST NOT begin with the <code>$</code> character"</em> —
  future spec growth can never collide with author names.
</p>
<p>
  The load-bearing move in every case: <strong>the standard concedes one side of a syntactic boundary to
  authors and permanently keeps the other for itself.</strong> No central "who owns which prefix" table is
  maintained — the platform did not solve collision by policing prefix ownership; it carved the namespace in
  two with one rule, so any author name is provably collision-free against the <em>entire current and future
  standard vocabulary</em>, with zero coordination. Collision detection then degrades to a cheap local check
  (the custom-elements <code>NotSupportedError</code> throw), and when even one namespace is too tight the
  answer is <strong>scoping</strong> (per-subtree registries), not a bigger reservation table.
</p>

<h2>Finding 2 — finer cross-author collision-avoidance anchors names to owned identity; namespace by ownership, NEVER by status</h2>
<p>
  The structural marker stops app-vs-<em>standard</em> collisions. App-vs-<em>app</em> collisions (two products
  both minting <code>card</code>) are solved by anchoring the name to something globally unique the author
  already controls: a DNS domain (RDF IRIs, Java <code>com.example.*</code>, schema.org external extensions),
  or a centrally-issued <strong>scope</strong> (npm <code>@scope/name</code>). DTCG applies exactly this to its
  extension keys — <em>"reverse domain name notation is recommended"</em> (<code>com.example.tool-a</code>).
  The per-<em>term</em> act needs no coordination: once you own the prefix, you mint freely, and two owners'
  prefixes can never coincide.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>The named guardrail is RFC 6648.</strong> The IETF used the same idea — prefix experimental
  parameters with <code>X-</code> to keep them out of the standard namespace — and then
  <strong>deprecated it</strong>: <em>"Creators of new parameters … SHOULD NOT prefix their parameter names
  with 'X-' or similar constructs."</em> The reason is precisely our scenario:
  <em>"Unstandardized parameters have a tendency to leak into the protected space of standardized parameters,
  thus introducing the need for migration from the 'X-' name to a standardized name. Migration, in turn,
  introduces interoperability issues."</em> <code>x-gzip</code> became a de-facto standard, the prefix
  <em>lied</em> about its status, and renaming it split old and new implementations forever. The lesson is
  sharp: <strong>namespace by OWNERSHIP (a scope/URI the author owns), never by STATUS</strong>
  (<code>custom-</code>, <code>x-</code>, <code>experimental-</code>). A status prefix is a future migration
  debt; an ownership prefix is stable across promotion — a custom intent graduating to standard becomes an
  <em>alias/registration</em>, not a rename.
</p>

<h2>Finding 3 — declarative/build-time registration is the schema-world norm; runtime registries pay for it</h2>
<p>
  Every <em>declarative</em> precedent registers <strong>build-time / statically</strong>: DTCG is a static
  JSON file; OpenAPI extensions live in the static description; Tailwind <code>@theme</code> and Style
  Dictionary compile before runtime. The payoff is that <strong>"what vocabulary exists" is answerable without
  running the app</strong> — statically analyzable, diffable, lintable. The two web-platform <em>runtime</em>
  registries (<code>customElements.define</code>, <code>CustomStateSet</code>) are imperative precisely
  because their members are <em>code</em> (a class, live element state) that can't be expressed as static
  data — and they pay for it: collision is a runtime throw, and the catalog is invisible to static tooling
  (custom states have <em>no</em> declarative surface at all).
</p>
<p>
  An intent is <strong>data</strong> (UX dimensions + values), not code — so it sits with the declarative
  precedents, not the runtime ones. This is reinforced by WE's own architecture: the intent→trait resolver
  <code>webtraits/intentProfileResolver.ts</code> is a <em>"pure, dependency-free resolver over the WE
  registries"</em> that returns a <em>build-time</em> bundle plan (<code>resolveTraits</code> /
  <code>bundlePlan</code>, scope per #776 is "build-time inclusion + delivery only"). A custom intent that
  resolves through this layer is naturally a build-time registration. CSS's duality is the useful nuance:
  <code>@property</code> shows the canonical shape — <strong>declarative-first, with an optional runtime
  escape hatch</strong> and a defined precedence when both exist.
</p>

<h2>Finding 4 — closed-vs-open is decided per intent by who must interoperate on the meaning</h2>
<p>
  ARIA puts two opposite choices in the <em>same</em> platform area. <strong>Roles are closed</strong> —
  authors can't mint them, unknown roles are ignored, and the only extension point is the
  <strong>fallback-token chain</strong> (<code>role="doc-biblioentry listitem"</code> degrades an unknown
  token to a known one). They're closed because a role is a <em>shared contract</em> with a third party the
  author doesn't control (assistive technology): an author-invented role is worthless because AT won't know
  it. <strong>Custom states are open</strong> — arbitrary author identifiers — because they're
  <em>component-private</em>: the meaning lives entirely between the element and its own stylesheet, so no
  external party needs to pre-agree; the platform still <em>fences</em> them behind a namespace marker.
</p>
<p>
  Transferred: WE should decide <em>per intent dimension/value</em> which lane it's in. WE already does this —
  the open-numbered <code>variant</code>/<code>tone</code>/<code>disposition</code> axes on Action Intent
  (<code>src/_data/intents/action.json</code>) are explicitly <em>"recommended core set, not a closed enum …
  authors may mint additional members"</em> (the <a href="/research/action-emphasis-axis/">#1318</a>
  open-numbered-variants contract). Custom <em>intents</em> are the next ring out: the same open-but-fenced
  discipline, applied to whole intents rather than to values within a standard intent.
</p>

<h2>Web-standards alignment</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Reserved structural marker</strong> (custom-elements dash, CSS <code>--</code>, DTCG <code>$</code>) —
    WE keeps standard intent ids bare/dash-free-equivalent and reserves a separator that names a custom intent,
    so a product intent can never collide with a current or future standard intent.</li>
  <li><strong>Ownership-anchored namespace</strong> (npm scope, reverse-DNS) — a custom intent carries its
    author's scope, so two products never collide.</li>
  <li><strong>Most-permissive default</strong> (<em>intents-are-UX-only</em> ruling) — an unknown intent
    degrades to the most-permissive default (ignored), mirroring JSON Schema's unknown-keyword-as-annotation,
    rather than throwing.</li>
  <li><strong>Declarative/build-time</strong> — fits <code>intentProfileResolver.ts</code> (a pure build-time
    function) and the one-file-per-entry registry convention (<code>src/_data/intents/</code>,
    <code>src/_data/researchTopics/</code>).</li>
</ul>

<h2>Recommendations for the decision</h2>

<h3>Namespacing convention</h3>
<p>
  <strong>Recommended: scope-style <code>owner:intent</code> (or <code>@owner/intent</code>), anchored to the
  product's existing app identity — not full reverse-DNS, not a bare status prefix.</strong> All four
  decentralized-naming precedents anchor to owned identity, but npm's choice is the tell: a <em>short
  centrally-issued scope</em> buys the same collision-freedom as reverse-DNS <em>without the dotted
  verbosity</em>, when the platform already has a notion of app identity (and WE/Plateau does — products have
  ids). The structural separator (the <code>:</code> / <code>@…/</code>) plays the custom-elements-dash role:
  standard intents stay bare (<code>action</code>, <code>navigation</code>), so a scoped id can never collide
  with a standard one, current or future. Explicitly <strong>reject a status prefix</strong>
  (<code>x-</code>, <code>custom-</code>) per RFC 6648 — it lies on promotion and forces a rename. Keep a
  schema.org-style <code>pending</code>/graduation path so a custom intent can be <em>aliased</em> into the
  standard catalog later, never renamed.
</p>

<h3>Build-time/declarative vs runtime/imperative</h3>
<p>
  <strong>Recommended: declarative, build-time registration — a per-product intent manifest globbed into the
  registry, exactly like <code>src/_data/intents/*.json</code> + <code>src/_data/researchTopics/</code>.</strong>
  The prior art overwhelmingly favors declarative for <em>data</em> vocabularies (DTCG, OpenAPI, Tailwind,
  Style Dictionary all build-time); only code-valued registries (custom elements, custom states) go runtime,
  and they lose static analyzability for it. An intent is data, and WE's resolver is already a pure build-time
  function — so build-time keeps the custom catalog diffable, lintable by <code>check:standards</code>, and
  answerable without running the app. <strong>Tradeoff / escape hatch:</strong> borrow CSS's
  <code>@property</code> duality — declarative-first with an <em>optional</em> runtime
  register-an-intent API for genuinely dynamic products (plugin hosts, user-authored dashboards), with the
  JS registration winning on a name tie. Pair it with JSON Schema's <code>$vocabulary</code> idea: a
  <code>mustUnderstand</code> opt-in so a product can declare "fail-fast if you don't know this intent" versus
  the default graceful-ignore.
</p>

<h3>Meta-schema shape (minimum fields)</h3>
<p>
  Mirror the existing intent JSON (<code>id</code> + <code>dimensions{ name → { description, values } }</code>),
  add namespacing + extension + provenance:
</p>
<pre><code class="language-jsonc">{
  "id": "acme:lozenge",            // scope-prefixed; standard ids stay bare
  "name": "Lozenge Intent",        // human label
  "extends": "tag",                // OPTIONAL — inherit a standard intent's dimensions, then add/override
  "dimensions": {                  // the UX axes (same shape as standard intents)
    "emphasis": {
      "description": "...",
      "values": ["subtle", "bold"],
      "default": "subtle"          // per-dimension most-permissive default (WE ruling)
    }
  },
  "mustUnderstand": false,         // OPTIONAL — false (default) = graceful ignore on unknown;
                                   //            true = fail-fast (JSON-Schema $vocabulary required-flag)
  "provenance": "com.acme",        // OWNER anchor (reverse-DNS or scope), for audit/dedupe — NOT status
  "$extensions": { }               // OPTIONAL — DTCG-style namespaced sidecar; MUST be preserved untouched
}</code></pre>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Required:</strong> <code>id</code> (scoped), <code>dimensions</code> with per-dimension
    <code>values</code> + <code>default</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>Recommended:</strong> <code>extends</code> (compose off a standard intent — Tailwind
    <code>extend</code> merge semantics, last-write-wins on dimension name), <code>provenance</code> (owner
    anchor), <code>mustUnderstand</code> (interop handshake).</li>
  <li><strong>Optional:</strong> <code>$extensions</code> (preserve-unknown sidecar) for tool-specific data
    that must round-trip without the engine understanding it.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The prepared forks</h2>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Fork 1 — Namespacing convention.</strong> Scope-style <code>owner:intent</code>
    <em>(recommended)</em> vs full reverse-DNS <code>com.acme.lozenge</code> (verbose; only pays off with no
    registry, which WE doesn't lack) vs a bare status prefix <code>custom-lozenge</code> (<strong>broken</strong>
    per RFC 6648 — lies on promotion).
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Fork 2 — Registration timing.</strong> Declarative build-time manifest <em>(recommended)</em> vs
    runtime register-API. Recommend declarative-first <strong>plus</strong> an optional runtime hatch
    (<code>@property</code> duality) for dynamic hosts.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Fork 3 — Unknown-intent behavior.</strong> Graceful most-permissive ignore <em>(recommended
    default)</em> vs throw. Recommend ignore-by-default with a per-intent <code>mustUnderstand:true</code>
    opt-in for fail-fast (JSON-Schema <code>$vocabulary</code> required-flag).
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Fork 4 — Composition.</strong> Allow <code>extends</code> a standard intent (merge/override
    dimensions, Tailwind-extend semantics) <em>(recommended)</em> vs standalone-only (forces re-declaring
    shared dimensions, drift).
  </li>
</ul>

